%I A392896 #29 Mar 30 2026 10:28:59
%S A392896 2,3,4,6,8,10,13,15,18,21,24,27,31,34,38,41,45,49,53,57,61,65,69,74,
%T A392896 78,82,87,91,96,101,105,110,115,119,124,129,134,139,144,149,154,159,
%U A392896 164,169,174,179,184,190,195,200,206,211,216,222,227,233,238,243,249,255,260,266,271,277
%N A392896 a(n) = least k >= 2 such that Sum_{i=2..k} 1/log(i) >= n.
%C A392896 The sum Sum_{i=2..k} 1/log(i) is asymptotic to li(k) - li(2), where li is the logarithmic integral. Hence a(n) is approximately the inverse logarithmic integral of n + li(2).
%C A392896 Analogous to A004080 (least k such that the harmonic number H(k) >= n), but with 1/log(k) replacing 1/k.
%C A392896 The first differences are nondecreasing and grow approximately as log(n).
%F A392896 a(n) ~ n*log(n) as n -> infinity. More precisely, a(n) is approximately li^(-1)(n + li(2)), where li^(-1) is the inverse of the logarithmic integral.
%e A392896 a(1) = 2 because 1/log(2) = 1.4427... >= 1.
%e A392896 a(4) = 6 because 1/log(2) + 1/log(3) + 1/log(4) + 1/log(5) + 1/log(6) = 4.2537... >= 4, while the sum up to k=5 is 3.6956... < 4.
%t A392896 a[n_]:=Module[{k=1},While[Sum[1/Log[i],{i,2,k}]<n,k++];k];Array[a,64] (* _James C. McMahon_, Mar 29 2026 *)
%Y A392896 Cf. A004080.
%K A392896 nonn,new
%O A392896 1,1
%A A392896 _Firdous Ahmad Mala_, Mar 24 2026
